I run my HomeLAN on LANtastic. Network interface cards are between $40 and $80 
each, node software is about $75-$85 each for the current version. Advantages 
are that you need not have anything but computers capable of running MS-DOS. 
LANtastic offers everything your standard PC LAN can do. 

One of the reasons I like LANtastic is that it lets you use old 286 hardware 
as dedicated servers. For big, heavily accessed networks the standard practice 
is to use big-time CPU's, fast buses, etc; but for small LANs using slow old 
stuff as a dedicated server makes all kinds of sense. For example, I have an 
AT with a hard drive running as dedicated server in my house. It handles all 
the print spooling/sharing and files/ap sharing between my wife and I. I've 
save the cost of a redundent printer and file sharing is much easier. You 
don't even need a monitor on the server once you have it set up, or you can 
use an old CGA or Herc Mono screen that you pick up at the electronic junk 
store.

